<div id="review_625388114" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/625388114" />
    <a title="Asif " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4671840-asif"><img alt="Asif " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1369595464p2/4671840.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/625388114?book_show_action=true">May 26, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Asif " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Asif " href="/user/show/4671840-asif">Asif </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4671840-asif?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4671840-asif?shelf=dark-love">dark-love</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4671840-asif?shelf=usa-fiction">usa-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer625388114" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12526293070409245025">I&apos;ve read this before but am now re-reading it after having watched the brilliant movie version again; it&apos;s a bleak movie and a bleaker novel but something in that darkness resonates with me and there is beauty in it too.<br/><br/>The movie is dark. The novel is much darker. This has to be the most devastatingly brilliant description of alcoholism in fiction. It’s harrowing. It depicts it as a disease and surely that’s what it is when it gets to the stage that Ben was in. The main differences from the mov</span>
  <span id="freeText12526293070409245025" style="display:none">I've read this before but am now re-reading it after having watched the brilliant movie version again; it's a bleak movie and a bleaker novel but something in that darkness resonates with me and there is beauty in it too.<br /><br />The movie is dark. The novel is much darker. This has to be the most devastatingly brilliant description of alcoholism in fiction. It’s harrowing. It depicts it as a disease and surely that’s what it is when it gets to the stage that Ben was in. The main differences from the movie were, apart from more detail and an insight into the protagonists thoughts which is hard to do in a film unless you use voice overs which can be annoying, that Sera’s pimp was not Russian but an Omani Arab, and the rape scene where she is raped by three college boys is at the beginning of the novel and not later. Other than that it’s a very faithful adaptation and one of the best ever. Both movie and novel are great. I’m going to read O’Brien’s other books but it will be a while before I stop thinking about this one. I’d love to know how Sera’s life panned out after the events of this novel. Haven’t been moved this much by a book in a long time. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12526293070409245025" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


