<div id="review_1575106660" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1575106660" />
    <a title="Derek" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6480250-derek"><img alt="Derek" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1353795932p2/6480250.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1575106660?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Derek" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Derek" href="/user/show/6480250-derek">Derek</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1575106660" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10315925679662391785">John O&apos;Brien&apos;s small novel has been unfairly forgotten in the shadow of its more famous movie relative. This is a shame because O&apos;Brien is an interesting literary hybrid: He&apos;s got the soul of Bukowski with Fitzgerald&apos;s flair for lyrical prose. I can&apos;t think of a lovelier or more heart-wrenching book that I&apos;ve come across recently.<br/>The novel is both unflinching and unrelenting. Redemption isn&apos;t sought after by any of the main characters; in truth, it isn&apos;t even on the agenda. The three central cha</span>
  <span id="freeText10315925679662391785" style="display:none">John O'Brien's small novel has been unfairly forgotten in the shadow of its more famous movie relative. This is a shame because O'Brien is an interesting literary hybrid: He's got the soul of Bukowski with Fitzgerald's flair for lyrical prose. I can't think of a lovelier or more heart-wrenching book that I've come across recently.<br />The novel is both unflinching and unrelenting. Redemption isn't sought after by any of the main characters; in truth, it isn't even on the agenda. The three central characters are all facing some sort of personal Armageddon but none of them are truly trying to escape it. <br />Knowing what plagued O'Brien and how it eventually overtook him, the novel can be hardgoing at times. He was no tourist and the pain depicted feels vitally real and hard-earned. But that makes the moments of beauty that occur throughout the book, and they are definitely there, genuine and true too. It's those moments, amidst all the ugly sadness, that give <i>Leaving Las Vegas</i> its power.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10315925679662391785" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


