<div id="review_342751417" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/342751417" />
    <a title="Diego Flores" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5438183-diego-flores"><img alt="Diego Flores" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1330655682p2/5438183.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/342751417?book_show_action=true">Jun 05, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Diego Flores" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Diego Flores" href="/user/show/5438183-diego-flores">Diego Flores</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer342751417" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12379426435074720852">Reading on an early train to work one morning, this book made me feel physically sick though I had not drank the night before and was feeling fine on the walk to the station. That isn&apos;t a criticism, but rather praise for how strongly the writing impresses upon you Ben&apos;s condition. With a lesser writer, Ben (who I could only picture as Nicholas Cage despite having never seen the movie) might have been too sympathetic or too unlikable. Instead what we get is an honest picture lacking in pretension</span>
  <span id="freeText12379426435074720852" style="display:none">Reading on an early train to work one morning, this book made me feel physically sick though I had not drank the night before and was feeling fine on the walk to the station. That isn't a criticism, but rather praise for how strongly the writing impresses upon you Ben's condition. With a lesser writer, Ben (who I could only picture as Nicholas Cage despite having never seen the movie) might have been too sympathetic or too unlikable. Instead what we get is an honest picture lacking in pretension. Along with the visceral descriptions of Ben's debilitating alcoholism, I found O'Brien's prose really enjoyable. Yep.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12379426435074720852" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


